messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

This should definitely close the door to any build executed by Docker server with an older image (e.g. see the old Bazel version that was recently detected in some nodes)

Patch Set 1:

I like it, but the configuration in the master's config.xml is not updated here. So the master does not automatically know which image version to use until this is set manually.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I like it, but the configuration in the master's config.xml is not updated here. So the master does not automatically know which image version to use until this is set manually.

It must be made through a different commit IMHO. You may or may not use what is built, or you could even rollback to an earlier version of that image when needed.

One thing is building the images, another thing is using them. WDYT?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > I like it, but the configuration in the master's config.xml is not updated here. So the master does not automatically know which image version to use until this is set manually.
> 
> It must be made through a different commit IMHO. You may or may not use what is built, or you could even rollback to an earlier version of that image when needed.

True. That is part of having versioned images.

> 
> One thing is building the images, another thing is using them. WDYT?

The thing is that with this commit, if I would build the images and start a Jenkins master and try to run jobs (without using images from docker hub), I would be unable to do so until I would configure the image tags in the configuration. I would like to avoid manual work :-).

Thus, I would prefer to have a sensible default that is automatically set. Solutions I can think of are:

- An easy solution would be to also always push all images with the latest tag in addition to the version tag and by default configure to use latest. That would automate it for test systems. Not a lot better IMHO, but would represent a workable state.

- We could use envsubst to also set the version in the config.xml, when building the master image. This way we would ensure that all docker images used are by default built from the same commit. The "disadvantage" would be that always all images will have to be built, but I think that would anyway be good practice.

WDYT?

BTW, in our fork, we also print the image versions (also derived from git describe) as the first build step in each job. I added that as a quick and dirty solution for us to know what container is actually used for the build job. That also allows users without admin rights to see that. If you think that would be useful in addition to your change, I would be happy to share the change. Should have done that earlier anyway :-(.
